Now,
 $x=7-y-z$.
Therefore $f(x,y,z)=yz(7-y-z)=-y^2z-yz^2+7yz=-yz(y+z-7)$</ think>
<answer>
\begin{align*}
f(x,y,z)=-yz(y+z-7)=-yz(7-y-2z)\\
&=-7yz+yz^2+2y^2z. & (1)
\end{align*}
Since $y+z=7-x \Rightarrow y=7-x-z$ and $y,z \ge0 \Rightarrow 7-x-z,z \ge0 \Rightarrow x \le 7$ and $0 \le z \le 7$, then $0 \le y \le 7$. (because $y+z=7-x$)
According to $xyz \ge 0$,then
\begin{align*}
yz\ge 0  & \Rightarrow -yz \ge 0\\
7-z & \Rightarrow 7-z \ge -2z \Rightarrow 7 \ge z \\
7-y &\Rightarrow 7-y \ge -z \Rightarrow 7 \ge -2y \\
\Rightarrow 7 \ge & z \ge 0; \, \, 0 \le y \le 7.
\end{align*}
$(1) -yz(y+z-7)=-7yz+yz^2+2y^2z$
From $(1)$, we have four cases:
I  if $y=0$, then expression I equals to
\begin{align*}
f(x,y,z)=-yz(y+z-7)=-yz(0+z-0)=-y^2z
\end{align*}
Since $0 \le y, z \le 7$, we have
\begin{align*}
-7^2\le -y^2z\le 0
\end{align*}
II. If $ z=0$, the expression is
\begin{align*}
f(x,y,z)=-yz(y+z-7)=-yz(0-0-7)=7yz
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
0\le 7yz \le 7*7^2=343
\end{align*}
III. If $y=z$,the expression is
\begin{align*}
f(x,y,z)=-yz*(2y-7)=-y^2(2y-7)=-2y^3+7y^2
\end{align*}
I need to find the range of $-2y^3+7y^2= y^2*(7-2y)$, which is the derivative of the function $f$ of $y$ in the range of $0 \le y \le 7$,
\begin{align*}
f'(y)=2y(7-2y)-y^2(2)=14y-6y^2-2y=12y-6y^2=-6y(y-2)
\end{align*}
Therefore, this $f$ has a critical point at $y=2$
\begin{align*}
f(0)=f(7)=0
\end{align*}
$f(2)=2*(7-4)=6$
The function $f(y)$ is maximum at $y=2$ and $f(2)=6$.
Therefore, $6 \le f(x,y,z) \le 343$.
(II) if $y=7-z$, the expression we got is
\begin{align*}
f(x,y,z)=z(7-z)(z-7)=-z(-7-2z)\\
=2z^2+7z
\end{align*}
$(f(z))'=4z+7, $ and for a critical point $z=0$
\begin{align*}
f(0)=0,  f(7)=0
\end{align*}
$|f(z)|_{\min}=0$, and $|f(z)|_{\max}=2*7^2+7*7 =147$.
Thus, we have the range $0 \le f(x,y,z) \le 147.$
So the range is $[0,343]$.
</ answer>

problem:
In the diagram, $QRS$ is a straight line. What is the measure of $\angle RPS,$ in degrees? [asy]
pair Q=(0,0);
pair R=(1.3,0);
pair SS=(2.3,0);
pair P=(.8,1);

draw(P--Q--R--SS--P--R);

label("$Q$",Q,S);
label("$R$",R,S);
label("$S$",SS,S);
label("$P$",P,N);

label("$48^\circ$",Q+(.12,.05),NE);
label("$67^\circ$",P-(.02,.15),S);
label("$38^\circ$",SS+(-.32,.05),NW);

[/asy]

solution:
Since the sum of the angles in a triangle is $180^\circ,$ then \begin{align*}
\angle QPS &= 180^\circ - \angle PQS - \angle PSQ \\
&= 180^\circ - 48^\circ - 38^\circ \\
&= 94^\circ.
\end{align*}Therefore, \begin{align*}
\angle RPS &= \angle QPS - \angle QPR \\
&= 94^\circ - 67^\circ \\
&= \boxed{27^\circ}.
\end{align*}

